  "prompt": "Can the statement \"X is n times less or smaller than Y be justified when n>1?",
  "response": "The statement \"X is n times less than Y\" when \\( n > 1 \\) can lead to confusion and is generally considered ambiguous or incorrect in mathematical terminology. \n\nTraditionally, \"X is n times less than Y\" might be interpreted as:\n\n\\[\nX = Y - nY = Y(1 - n)\n\\]\n\nHowever, this interpretation results in a negative value for \\( X \\) if \\( n > 1 \\), which may not make sense in many contexts.\n\nA more precise way to express the relationship is to say, \"X is \\( 1/n \\) times Y\" or \"Y is \\( n \\) times X\" if you want to indicate that \\( X \\) is proportionally smaller than \\( Y \\) by a factor of \\( n \\). \n\nIn summary, while you might encounter the phrase \"X is n times less than Y\" in colloquial usage, it's mathematically clearer to avoid it and use exact terms that convey the intended meaning.",
